<br>
STILLWATER, Minn., <br>
<br>
May 19 <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/21/science/physical/21ESSA.html?ex=1022644800&amp;en=f1ce92c9e923d979&amp;ei=5040&amp;partner=MOREOVER">Source.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
In a kind of writer's convalescence, I have come here to rediscover the intellectual pleasures of pure physics and cosmology.<br>
<br>
Before being thrown into nearly continuous coverage of the World Trade Center disaster since Sept. 11, I had spent years absorbing and explaining the insights of those fields, first for my doctoral thesis in astrophysics, then as a science reporter. Here at a forest-shrouded lodge achatter with the camaraderie of some of the world's smartest people, I am attending my first major scientific conference since that terrible day.<br>
<br>
My convalescence is not going well. The collapse of two skyscrapers brimming with life has darkened my view of the glittering but chilly cosmos, at least when viewed through the lens that science gives me.<br>
<br>
Scientists have a preoccupation with the most energetic and violent events in the cosmos ・galaxy-rending blasts like gamma ray bursts, lesser outbursts like exploding stars, and the mother of all cataclysms, the Big Bang. Those displays provide some of the most stringent tests of advanced scientific theories, and they also reveal a kind of cosmic grandeur to scientists' eyes, something like their version of the Sistine Chapel.<br>
<br>
The physical laws that produced this grandeur, scientists believe, almost certainly produced life, sentient beings and civilizations elsewhere in the cosmos, where the same laws hold. The cute, colorful screen savers for SETI (the Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence) will surely one day begin blipping or bleeping ・whatever they are programmed to do when a signal arrives from out yonder.<br>
<br>
Given all this, I find myself, post-9/11, in the position of some Vietnamese orphans a friend once told me about, who were taken in by a church group. On the Fourth of July, the group took the children to see some fireworks, since all children love fireworks. But these children started to cry: the fireworks reminded them too much of bombing.<br>
<br>
Now, when I look into the sky that science has revealed, the idea of a cosmos teeming with advanced life and rent by immeasurable blasts opens an unexpected wound. The idea that the lovely sciences of materials, heat conduction, gravitation and others combine to explain not just why the towers stood but how they failed puts them in the same family tree as the blasts in distant space. For me, now, the physics of sudden demise is written in the sky.<br>
<br>
These days, I cannot understand why scientists have scarcely if ever put together the oh-so-cool cataclysms with the oh-so-cute screen savers and at least made an attempt to explain to us what all of this implies about the kind of universe we live in.<br>
<br>
Should we envision entire worlds trapped and nearing annihilation by one of those spectacular cosmic blasts? Will the screen savers that blip with life then begin flatlining as our telescopes pick up the gamma ray burst that snuffed it all out? Will the screen savers still be cute then?<br>
<br>
Physicists have occasionally expressed dread over the power of their own creations. As he watched the first atomic bomb test, J. Robert Oppenheimer, the physicist who directed the project, said he recalled a line attributed to the god Shiva in the Bhagavad-Gita: &quot;Now I am become death, destroyer of worlds.&quot;<br>
<br>
But serious study of the cosmos has spread through physics only recently. In any case, even Oppenheimer's reference would probably sound like mystical mush to most of today's scientists, who have developed an institutional aversion to theism of any kind.<br>
<br>
So I tried some of my nontheistic ruminations on some of the thinkers at the gathering here, called the Seven Pines Symposium, with a mix of predictable and surprising results.<br>
<br>
Bruce Winstein, a physicist and cosmologist at the University of Chicago, said scientists pondered such questions more often than they let on. &quot;We all do secretly,&quot; Dr. Winstein said. &quot;We just don't talk about it.&quot;<br>
<br>
In fact, Dr. Winstein recalled, when as a young scientist he was first learning about Big Bang, the nonpareil blast that is believed to have spawned the universe, he found it all rather frightening, &quot;an incredibly scary time.&quot;<br>
<br>
But he eventually came to terms with the Big Bang, and has since made a profession of observing its afterglow, the cosmic microwave background radiation. For him, now, the periodic cataclysms that may have wiped out civilizations are little different from the cruel ・but unavoidable ・Darwinian survival of the fittest that takes place in any earthly ecosystem, Dr. Winstein said.<br>
<br>
A universe that simply wipes out its progeny over light-years of space does not evoke a Darwinian struggle, but rather cosmic waste.<br>
<br>
But as another scientist here pointed out, those great explosions also generate chemical elements heavier than iron, which seem to be absolute requirements for complex life to evolve in the first place.<br>
<br>
Jed Buchwald, a historian of science at the California Institute of Technology, explained over a single-malt Scotch here that physicists in particular have long had a special loathing for admitting questions with the slightest emotional content into their professional work.<br>
<br>
That clinical approach yields many fruitful results, but it &quot;wipes out completely the transcendent dimension,&quot; Dr. Buchwald said. <br>
<br>
At their meeting here, scientists have had intense discussions about universes with as many as 11 dimensions in ordinary space and time. Since the towers fell, surely there is room in the cosmos for the small additional one that Dr. Buchwald mentioned.<br>
